image.altText: A man in a white shirt looks towards the camera.

props.synopsis: Simon Burgess, a two-time Olympic medallist, is given a suspended jail sentence for assaulting his ex-wife in her home in 2023, with the court hearing he was embarrassed about the effect of his conduct on his wider family.

title.children: Dual Olympic rowing medallist avoids further jail after assaulting ex-wife in her home

image.altText: Road works crew at construction site, unspecified location.

props.synopsis: In 2010, three workers were poisoned by toxic gas from an old underground pipe. Now there is a push to do something about the "potentially fatal" risk — but the company that owned the pipes went bust and nobody knows where they are anymore.

title.children: Deadly gas lying in wait in underground pipes beneath two Tasmanian cities

image.altText: A krill processing ship near a surfacing whale.

props.synopsis: At the meeting between 26 member countries, proposals to establish new marine protected areas and revise catch limits for krill are rejected, while existing krill management measures are rolled back. Australia says it's a "backwards step", putting the Antarctic ecosystem at risk.

title.children: Australia labels Antarctic conservation meeting 'backwards step' after Russia and China block all proposals

image.altText: A large, red ferry with a smaller pilot boat in front

props.synopsis: As Tasmania's government points to direct flights between Hobart and Auckland as a win for the local tourism sector, one caravan park operator says his park had a third of its usual late October visitors — and has fired a shot across the bow of the Spirit of Tasmania ferry operator.

title.children: Spirit of Tasmania saga fallout continues as state government welcomes direct flight link to New Zealand

image.altText: Kate's Berry Farm exterior of buildings.

props.synopsis: After Kate Bradley "started life again" at age 43 in Tasmania, she decided to plant berries and sell ice cream. Thirty-five years on, after much success (and false starts), she looks back with pride — and is ready to move on from the business she built, much of it by her own hands.

title.children: After 'starting again' aged 43, Kate built her dream with her own hands

image.altText: IMAGE slime moulds shiny

props.synopsis: Deep in the bush of northern Tasmania, Sarah Lloyd is crouched over a mossy log holding a magnifying glass brimming with quiet excitement. She is hunting for slime moulds.

title.children: Step into the 'beautiful' and 'quite unexpected' world of slime moulds

image.altText: Three men in high vis and hard hats talk to the media

props.synopsis: Tasmania's business and tourism groups have grown increasingly fed up with the state government over its handling of the new Spirit of Tasmania vessels. That anger overflowed on Thursday.

title.children: Did you miss? 📣 'A calamity for Tasmania': Premier wanted calm seas over Spirits fiasco, but now he faces a storm

image.altText: Two men in suits stand on either side of a woman on the white steps of a large building.

props.synopsis: David Crisafulli has been sworn in as Queensland's premier today, vowing to legislate his key crime policy before the end of the year.

title.children: David Crisafulli sworn in as Queensland premier after LNP wins state election

image.altText: Elon Musk holds up a fist. He is wearing a gold 'Make America Great Again' baseball cap.

props.synopsis: Elon Musk has promised to give away $US1 million a day leading up to the United States presidential election, but legal experts warn the move could open "a new avenue for wealthy special interest money" in American politics.

title.children: The world's richest man and his million-dollar giveaways could help make Trump president

image.altText: A crowd of densely packed Palestinian people in distress reach for an open bakery window

props.synopsis: As an Israeli offensive in the north of the Gaza Strip enters a fourth week, local residents say they are starving as aid convoys are blocked from reaching them.

title.children: 'Conditions of life untenable' in northern Gaza, UN says, as dozens killed in one day

image.altText: Donald Trump speaks into a microphone in front of a red, white and blue screen.

props.synopsis: The gender divide in politics is a sleeper issue in Australia, with men and women — particularly young people — moving apart in profound and polarising ways, as opinions of the upcoming US election show.

title.children: Troubling split emerges in Australia over Trump

image.altText: A woman looks with at the camera with her hands up, smiling. She has big headphones on and a sign which says ABC Radio Sydney.

props.synopsis: The journalist has taken the broadcaster to the Federal Court after she was taken off air part way through a radio presenting stint on ABC Radio Sydney last December. It came after she shared a social media post on the war in Gaza.

image.altText: Close-up of Gina Chick with closed mouth, slightly smiling, with chin held slightly raised. Brown furry coat just visible.

props.synopsis: Gina Chick's sheer love of life is inspiring. Now she wants to use the profile she's gained from winning SBS's Alone Australia to help others appreciate the "wild adventure of life".

title.children: She was called 'too much' but Gina Chick wouldn't make herself small. Now she's helping others live big, too

image.altText: A graduate holds on to his hat while talking on his mobile phone

image.altText: Dark roof with solar panels

props.synopsis: The polling shows solid support for negative gearing and capital gains tax changes, but stronger support for more supply and first home buyer grants.

image.altText: A man stands in the doorway of an outbuilding, looking on.

image.altText: Q+A Health Special pre-show wrap

image.altText: People standing in mud clearing out homes

image.altText: Prabha Kumar, smiling at the camera in a bright pink and gold traditional outfit.

image.altText: A man sitting in a traditional shop in a market selling eggs, rice, oil.

props.synopsis: While Australia struggles to tackle the rising cost of living, other countries have the opposite problem. What is deflation and why can it be bad for the economy?

title.children: Prices have been dropping in Indonesia. It has some economists concerned

image.altText: A man sits smiling under a wall made of timber and tin.

image.altText: A man speaks into a mic with an emphatic expression

props.synopsis: Evo Morales says he survived an assassination attempt on Sunday after unidentified men opened fire on his car. He was not injured in the alleged attack.

title.children: Bolivian ex-president shares video of escape from 'assassination attempt' as car sprayed with bullets

image.altText: Prime Minister Shigeru Ishiba at press conference

props.synopsis: Prime Minister Shigeru Ishiba's Liberal Democratic Party has ruled for almost all of Japan's postwar period. But it lost its parliamentary majority at Sunday's national election. Could smaller parties be key for Japan's future government?

title.children: Japan's long-running governing party loses majority, raising uncertainty over next government

image.altText: A middle-aged brunette woman in white speaks at a white lectern backed by red and white Georgian flags

title.children: US calls for investigation into Georgia's contested election

image.altText: A couple inspects their unfinished Nicheliving home.

image.altText: Three girls smile at camera near show rides

props.synopsis: Community events are a lifeline for rural and regional towns across Australia, but more organisers are making the "heartbreaking" decision to cancel them.

props.synopsis: Jayden Daniels gets away with a stunning Hail Mary to sink the Bears, as Jordan Love goes down for the Packers. Here at the five quick hits from the NFL action.
